The two-color fluorescent probe CDs@Fe/Zr-MOF was formed by simple physical mixing of CDs and Fe/Zr-MOF with the help of electrostatic attraction. At the excitation wavelength of 365 nm, CDs emitted green fluorescence at 505 nm in the system, and Fe/Zr-MOF emitted a wavelength of 450 nm blue fluorescence (

                           Fig. S13

                        ). The fluorescence yields of CDs and Fe/Zr-MOF are 1.71 % and 6.26 %, respectively, which have good luminescence properties and can be used for detection. When the excitation wavelength is 365 nm, with the increase of SP and HIS solution, the green fluorescence was increased while the blue-fluorescence intensity was decreased, which can be observed in 3D emission profiles (

                           Fig. S9

                        ). The two-color fluorescent probe CDs@Fe/Zr-MOF changed from dark blue to blue-green and then to green, with a relatively obvious change.

To realize field detection, make better use of fluorescence ratio detection, and reduce the judgment error of human eyes, an intelligent fluorescence sensing system was successfully constructed. The smartphone fluorescence sensing system includes a 3D printing box, a smartphone, a cuvette, a power supply, a UV light source, and an applet. Based on the deep learning model, with the aid of a smartphone taking photos and capturing images, the applet used the YOLO V3 algorithm to classify images of the system and automatically divided them, and extracted HSV and RGB signal values with the image processing algorithm. According to the color change, the data processing channel was selected to extract the extracted signal value, to fit the linear relationship between the concentration and the channel value. Before the applet was put into use, a large number of deep learning models were prepared. 111 fluorescence images were collected, including a variety of cuvets with different fluorescence colors and different angles, which were divided into 40 % test set and 60 % training set. Upload the photo album to the mini-program, use the YOLO V3 algorithm (
                        Fig. 3

                        ) for classification and labeling, adjust the size of the input image to 416*416, and predict three feature layers (global features of 13*13 feature layer and local features of 26*26 and 52*52 feature layer), to achieve a better detection effect (Wang et al., 2021).

To verify the feasibility of the smart fluorescent label and explore its universality, pork and shrimp were selected as actual samples. First, put pork, and whole shrimp of the same quality in a petri dish. The prepared fluorescent hydrogel label was then placed in a petri dish to avoid direct contact between the samples and the labels. Afterward, the containers used for the experiment should be sealed from light and kept at three different temperatures (−20 °C, 4 °C, and 35 °C) lasting 0–48 h (
                        Fig. 5

                        ). During this period, under ultraviolet light, the smartphone photo was taken to collect the fluorescent image of the smart tag. The color of the fluorescent labels in the different Petri dishes started blue, and over time the blue became darker, gradually changing to blue-green and then dark green. In addition to images under UV light, images under fluorescent light were also collected.
